revision.text:
{{Infobox legislation |short_title = |legislature = Scottish Parliament |image = |imagesize = |imagealt = |caption = |long_title = Abolition of Poindings and Warrant Sales Act 2001 |citation = |enacted_by = Tommy Sheridan |date_enacted = |date_passed = |enacted_by2 = |date_enacted2 = |date_passed2 = |date_assented = |royal_assent = |date_commenced = |bill = |bill_citation = |bill_date = |introduced_by = |1st_reading = |2nd_reading = |3rd_reading = |committee_report = |bill2 = |bill_citation2 = |bill_date2 = |introduced_by2 = |1st_reading2 = |2nd_reading2 = |3rd_reading2 = |committee_report2 = |white_paper = |amendments = |repeals = 2002 |related_legislation = Debt Arrangement and Attachment (Scotland) Act 2002 |summary = Amended the Debtors (Scotland) Act 1987 |keywords = |status = repealed }}
The '''Abolition of Poindings and Warrant Sales Act 2001''' was an [[Act of the Scottish Parliament]] to abolish the previous practice in which a debtor’s goods are priced ([[poinding]]) in preparation for the enforced sale of the debtor’s possessions ([[warrant sale]]). The legislation was introduced in 1999 as a [[member's bill]] by [[Tommy Sheridan]] [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSP]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.scot/S1_Bills/Abolition%20of%20Poindings%20and%20Warrant%20Sales%20Bill/b3s2.pdf |title=Text of the Stage 2 Bill |publisher=Scottish Parliament |accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> the sole member of the [[Scottish Socialist Party]] in the Parliament.
The original draft of the bill proposed that it would have immediate effect, but this was subsequently amended to delay implementation of the bill until 2002, so that alternative means of debt recovery could be devised.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1058426.stm|title=MSPs abolish warrant sales|date=6 December 2000|accessdate=24 November 2016|publisher=''BBC News''}}</ref> The [[Scottish Executive]] eventually proposed the Debt Arrangement and Attachment Bill,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1973831.stm|title=Ministers unveil debt proposals |work=BBC News|date=8 May 2002|accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref> which became the Debt Arrangement and Attachment Bill Act 2002 and repealed the Abolition of Poindings and Warrant Sales Act.
The Debt Arrangement and Attachment Act was criticised by Sheridan for introducing "a new form of warrant sales".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/msps-attack-new-debt-recovery-law-1-950593|title=MSPs attack new debt recovery law |work=The Scotsman|date=9 May 2002|accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref>
