'''Jonas Öberg''' (born 22 November 1977 in Sweden) is a free and open-source software activist, describing himself as an instigator in the world of free,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jonaso|title=Twitter account @jonaso|accessdate=2013-03-27}}</ref> having worked with the [[Free Software Foundation Europe]],<ref name="Andersson2013">{{cite news|first=Niklas|last=Andersson|title=Öppen källkod det var så det började|work=IDG Techworld|date=21 February 2013}}</ref> [[GNU Project]],<ref name="gnu">{{cite web|url=https://www.gnu.org/people/people.en.html|title=GNU's Who|accessdate=15 April 2013}}</ref> [[FSCONS]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Kenneth|last=Frantzén|url=http://www.hackerpublicradio.org/eps.php?id=1087|title=hpr1087 :: The FSCONS of Jonas Öberg|work=Hacker Public Radio|date=1 October 2012}}</ref> [[Creative Commons]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/28686|title=Announcing the Creative Commons Global Summit - New Creative Commons Regional Managers|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref> and the [[Shuttleworth Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Gunilla|last=Larsson|title=Göteborgs-Posten Namn|work=Göteborgs-Posten|date=2 January 2013}}</ref> He started to develop software in 1991 and installed his first GNU/Linux operating system in 1993<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fscons.org/2007/node/13|title=Interview with Jonas Öberg|year=2007|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref> after which he eventually joined as a webmaster for the [[GNU Project]].<ref name="gnu" /> In the late 1990s, he spent some time at the [[MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory|MIT AI Labs]] where he met with [[Richard Stallman]] and others from the [[Free Software Foundation]], joining them for The Bazaar conference in New York.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mikael|last=Pawlo|title=Gnuheter intervjuar Jonas Öberg|date=5 December 2001|work=Gnuheter}}</ref> Since 2002, he has been on the award committee for the [[Free Software Foundation]]'s [[FSF Free Software Awards|Free Software Awards]].

In 2001, he was a founding member of the [[Free Software Foundation Europe]]<ref name="Andersson2013" /> and took up a role as vice president on 22 November 2001 when former vice president [[Loïc Dachary]] took a step back to focus on [[GNU Savannah]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lists.softwarelibero.it/pipermail/discussioni/2001-December/002825.html|title=FSFE press release|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref>

Having worked with [[Creative Commons]] for several years, including running a course of fundraising at the [[Peer to Peer University]], he became the first Regional Coordinator for Europe in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/28686|title=Creative Commons blog|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref> His work for the organisation eventually led him to a position as a Fellow of the [[Shuttleworth Foundation]] where his work focus on creating tools and prototypes for the embedding of metadata for licensing and attribution requirements in digital works.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shuttleworthfoundation.org/fellows/jonas-oberg/|title=Shuttleworth Foundation: Jonas Öberg|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref> His company [[Commons Machinery]] was featured as one of the 12 winners of Tech All Stars 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/digital-agenda/en/news/clear-returns-wins-tech-all-stars-2014-eus-top-startup-competition|title=Tech All Stars 2014 Winners|accessdate=2014-06-21}}</ref> a competition of the [[European Commission]]'s and [[Neelie Kroes]]'s Digital Agenda.

== Personal life ==

He has a 19th-century wooden house in the North of Sweden which he is continuously renovating<ref>{{cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/staff#jonasoberg|title=Creative Commons staff list|accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref> and lives outside of [[Stockholm]] in [[Gnesta]], [[Sweden]]. He married [http://phd.nordkonst.org Julia Velkova] - a media researcher, and a member of [[Internet Society]] Bulgaria. Their marriage took place at the [[Ice hotel]] in Sweden on 8 March 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kalle|last=Sandhammar|work=Norrländska Socialdemokraten|date=12 March 2013|title=Vigslar}}</ref>

