{{Politics of Peru}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Peru]] on 31 October 1993. It followed the [[Alberto Fujimori]]'s [[1992 Peruvian constitutional crisis|presidential coup]] on 5 April 1992.<ref name=DD>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=pe011993 Peru, 31 October 1993: Constitution] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref> A new constitution was published on 4 September 1993, limiting the President to two terms of four years, creating a [[unicameralism|unicameral]] [[Congress of the Republic of Peru|Congress]]. Constitutional amendments would be possible with either a referendum or a two-thirds majority in two successive Congresses.<ref name=DD/> Referendums would also be possible if a petition had 0.3% of voters' signatures.<ref name=DD/> After being approved by 52% of voters, the [[Constitution of Peru|new constitution]] came into force on 29 December 1993.<ref name=DD/>
